TY  - JOUR
T1  - Bounds on specification error arising from data proxies
AU  - Kroch, Eugene
JO  - Journal of Econometrics
VL  - 37
IS  - 1
SP  - 171
EP  - 192
PY  - 1988
DA  - 1988/01/01/
SN  - 0304-4076
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0304-4076(88)90081-4
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0304407688900814
AB  - Specification error that arises when the researcher is forced to work with data ‘proxies’ can be treated as a general error in the underlying variable. This paper explores the relation between the ambiguity of possible estimates and the size and form of the specification error. The trade-off between the strength of assumptions about misspecification and the resulting inferential uncertainty can be developed formally. In some cases what appear to be innocuous errors in proxies create very substantial inferential ambiguity. But in other cases fairly weak assumptions about specification error can reduce inferential uncertainty enormously.
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Is a philosophical consensus for statistics attainable?
AU  - Durbin, J.
JO  - Journal of Econometrics
VL  - 37
IS  - 1
SP  - 51
EP  - 61
PY  - 1988
DA  - 1988/01/01/
SN  - 0304-4076
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0304-4076(88)90073-5
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0304407688900735
AB  - The paper argues that most discussions of statistical inference are too narrowly conceived. Consideration of the biological evolution of the human intellect leads to a pragmatic appreciation of the role of logical systems in inference. Modern computing availability provides an incentive for a flexible attitude to practical data analysis. The case is argued for a unified philosophy of statistics in which techniques from different schools are accomodated in a spirit of objectivity and tolerance. The arguments are illustrated by a study of the effects of seatbelt legislation on road casualties.
ER  - 

