TY  - JOUR
T1  - Large-sample properties of method of moment estimators under different data-generating processes
AU  - Van Praag, B.M.S.
AU  - Kloek, T.
AU  - De Leeuw, J.
JO  - Journal of Econometrics
VL  - 37
IS  - 1
SP  - 157
EP  - 169
PY  - 1988
DA  - 1988/01/01/
SN  - 0304-4076
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0304-4076(88)90080-2
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0304407688900802
AB  - In this paper we study the large-sample properties of method of moment estimators (MME) of population parameters β that result as explicit or implicit solitions of equations ƒ(μ, β) = 0, where μ is a vector of moments. The distribution of the corresponding large-sample estimator b resulting from solving ƒ(m, b) = 0, where m is a sample moment estimator of μ, is shown to vary with the sample design. We study the case of a random sample, of a pooled sample, a sample from a known population distribution, and a so-called repeated sample. Also we provide a numerical example. Our main conclusion is that any seemingly harmless assumption on the sample design may have severe repercussions on the estimation of confidence bounds. Therefore we advocate to take a kind of minimal set of assumptions unless we have hard a priori knowledge.
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - The statistical approach to economics
AU  - Klein, Lawrence R.
JO  - Journal of Econometrics
VL  - 37
IS  - 1
SP  - 7
EP  - 26
PY  - 1988
DA  - 1988/01/01/
SN  - 0304-4076
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0304-4076(88)90071-1
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0304407688900711
AB  - The philosophical foundations of statistical methods in economics are presented in terms of the samples used and the non-experimental nature of the subject. Attention is paid to the degree of precision of economic data. The methods of economic statistics can be descriptive or inferential and the latter approach is exemplified through the technique of model building. Examples of macro- and microeconometric models are given, together with their implications for statistical method. The model building approach is contrasted with pure statistical analysis, which is empirical and not as closely related to received economic theory as is model building. The testing and using of models is taken up. All econometric models are not based on the methods of statistical inference. By contrast, descriptive measurement models and those based rigorously on equilibrium analysis are also discussed. Finally, the role of the computer in the development of econometrics is discussed.
ER  - 

